column168: Description Of Events

During the final inspection of the waste before loading it for outbound transportation to the disposal facility, a 55 gallon metal open top drum was found to have a pinhole leak in the sidewall that was not apparent on Friday during the facility inspection. The drum was promptly overpacked. Approximately ~100 ml of liquid was cleaned up from the pallet it leaked onto.

column168: While loading a pallet of lab pack containers onto a trailer at the Veolia 10 day intransit facility in Dayton, OH, a Veolia operator noticed an odor coming from the pallet. Initially, the employee did not see any damaged or wet boxes, so he proceeded to break down the pallet to inspect each box. After breaking down the pallet, a wet Questar box (141G) was discovered. Veolia estimates approximately one quart of liquid was released during the spill, most of which was absorbed by the fiber box. It appears that a bottle of allyl bromide broke in transit leading to the saturation of the box and release of liquid. The small amount of liquid that was released outside of the fiber box remained on the pallet under the box. The leaking box and spill pads used to clean up the spill were overpacked together for continued transportation to the final disposal facility.
column169: Veolia's safety manager will remind the team that when shipping a package containing inner containers of liquid material a sufficient amount of vermiculite or spill dry should be used to cushion the inner containers during transportation. The vermiculite or spill dry must be in a quantity that will be able to absorb the entire contents of the liquid material. The proper amount of cushioning should be used to ensure glass bottles do not break as a truck or trailer travels down the road.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LDA experienced a battery acid release from a 2300-pound UN2794 battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of battery acid released impacting the trailer floor and an 8' x 30' area of concrete lot below due to the battery falling off a forklift. Absorbents and neutralizer were deployed and utilized to clean the released acid. The battery was decontaminated, the caps were re-secured, and the battery was secured for shipment on. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were containerized into a 55-gallon and 30-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LHO experienced a UN3264 Bonderite M-ZN 450R release from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. column168: During off loading, technicians at the receiving facility observed a cubic yard fiberboard container of hazardous debris was smoldering. The debris was contaminated with acetone and methyl ethyl ketone. The technicians isolated the container to an area of the receiving pad and extinguished with an ABC extinguisher. The contents were repacked to a new container and dry ice was added. The repackaged material was scanned with an RFID camera and determined not to have an elevated temperature.  While unloading the remaining containers of debris, technicians found that a drum of methyl methacrylate had partially released some of its contents. The material solidified as expanded foam. The solidified material was repackaged and sampled for analysis. All containers on the trailer were imaged with RFID camera and found to not exhibit elevated temperatures.   No materials were released.
column169: The incident is in investigation. The generator is implementing corrective actions.

column168: On 7/7/2023, at 11:00 am driver prepared to deliver Sodium Bisulfite 38% - NaHS03.The driver pulled the hose out from the hose reel. During the initial hook up to the customers tank with the pump engaged, the connection between the hose reel and hose assembly began leaking in the reel box, causing a release of product on the ground. After shutting down the system, the customer immediately was informed and they were able to contain the product from all ditches and drains, then used an on-site vacuum truck to collect the spill. The driver informed his supervisor, the supervisor informed his manager. The amount of the spill was approximately 55 gallons. There was no exposure to any of the customer employees or Univar employee. There were no injuries

column168: Lone Star Hazmat Response was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 5ft-by-5ft area of the trailer floor and a 2ft-by-2ft area of asphalt yard.  Lone Star Hazmat Response personnel estimated that  five (5) gallons of material was released due to  loose caps on almost  all the 1-gallon plastic jugs on the pallet. Lone Star Hazmat Response deployed Sodium Bicarbonate to neutralize the impacted areas and then placed down Oil Dri as an absorbent. The spent material was gathered and placed into two 55-gallon poly drums along with the impacted cardboard. The impacted 1-gallon plastic jugs were containerized into two 95-gallon poly drums and two (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The generated waste was labeled and staged in a secure location onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: While loading the IBC into a van trailer, a Veolia operator noticed the IBC had leaked nearly a gallon of waste on to the ground. The leak appeared to be coming from a outlet on the bottom of the valve. The valve would have to fail for this to happen. The outlet was plugged with spill pads temporarily to contain the leak and the waste was transferred in to another tote for continued transportation to the disposal facility.
column169: Veolia will retrain personnel on container inspection prior to shipment from the customer. However, please note,  the valve did not fail until it was on the dock at Veolia 10 day intransit facility in Baytown, TX. There was no failure of the tote while the package was in public transportation. The Veolia crew who picked up the package from the shipper would have never known the valve was going to fail but the container did appear to be aged.

SequenceEvent: Package was found wet in load 2 after being dropped off by the tugger. Package had Corrosive HazMat labeling and was determined to be a HazMat. One of the packages corners was wet and leaking. Package was immediately taken out of the load areas and isolated from the rest of the staff. DescribePack: All 4 of the bottle's caps were taped down, in what seems to be an attempt to fix the leak. However, this did not work, and 2 of the 4 bottles began leaking out of their caps. The seals to each of the items were faulty and did not prevent any leakage. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: Package was taken to the HazMat cage for isolation and processing.

column168: SequenceEvent: The package was unloaded from the trailer and placed on the ground. Was informed by the manager who opened the trailer door that it smelled very strong as soon as he lifted the door.  He noticed the hazmat package right then and notified QA personnel immediately. The hazmat package was slightly leaking so it was placed in a hazardous materials tote and taken to the hazmat processing area for further inspection. Spill was very miniscule as the fiberboard absorbed majority of the liquid. DescribePack: The outside of the package is labeled "CONTAINS 12 - 1 LITERS" but inside the package were only 4 - 1 Liter plastic bottles with no other packaging material to prevent movement. The amount of empty space and room for bottles to move about during transit caused a lid on one of the 1-Liter bottles to open, resulting in 1/2 liter spill from the inside of the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The manager who lifted the trailer door and unloaded the package immediately let QA personnel know and put the strong smelling package in a tote away from the area. The trailer was checked for any further spillage and QA personnel took the hazmat to the hazmat processing area right away so the smell would not negatively affect the package handlers who would soon be unloading the trailer.

SequenceEvent: At the beginning of the sort this package came out of a trailer during unload and was placed on a spill tray until QA could retrieve it. When QA retrieved it they put on nitrile gloves, and placed the damaged item in 2 plastic non-haz bags and then into a lined bin. QA took the time to look around the area for any residue to clean it up off the surface(s). Using a cart the damaged package was wheeled over to the QA station in unload. DescribePack: Due to leaks from the items inside the outer box got wet and due to the corrosive nature of the cleaner a hole was created on the side of the package about the size of 2 fists. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The manager in the unload put the damaged box onto a spill tray and QA used non-haz bags and also put it into a lined bin for good measure. QA also went a bit further and inspected the surrounding area where the package came out of from the trailer as well as around the spill tray to soak/clean up any remaining residue.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Reported to be releasing vapor and green-yellow crust on the car.  Upon arrival a vapor cloud was present.  Upon further assessment and opening the housing cover, liquid was visibly releasing from between the valve and the 4-bolt flanged cover plate.  One bolt was missing a nut (found on the pressure plate), one nut was loose.  Crew attempted to tighten without stopping the leak.  The crew re-entered and loosened the flange, the leak did not worsen so the flange was removed.  Product was on top of the ball valve and was swirling.  The gasket had a depressed area and was changed out.  The flange was tightened, and the leak continued.  The liquid valve was cycled several times and the flange removed.  The product was no longer moving.  The gasket was flipped over, flange tightened, and the leak stopped.  Upon arrival of the shipper, the flange was removed, the product was removed off the ball valve, filled with water, and ensured the ball valve was secured with no releases.  No releases were observed, no liquid emitted from the ball valve.  A new Teflon gasket was installed, the flange resecured, and the car diverted back to origination.
column169: Ensure that the car is properly secured and ready for release into transportation.
